<hl>
<seg id=1> China plans to fill in coastal lowlands in order to build housing for people. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP Beijing) The English version of the Chinese Daily reported yesterday, china plans to fill in the shallows along the coast in order to provide residential land for 20,000,000 - 30,000,000 people in the next century. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> At a meeting held in Xiaoshan, Zhejiang province, the specialists revealed that, the government hopes to gain 1,000,000 hectare land by fill in areas of the coast along 18,000 kilometers. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The Chinese Daily said that, 20,000,000 - 30,000,000 people are going to live in these areas in the next century. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> This newspaper quoted Professor Zhiyan Yu as saying: "China has no technical problems to achieve this goal, however, the problem is there is not enough money." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The news reported that, this plan will cause prodigious environmental problems. "However, it is still a magic weapon to ease the serious shortage of land resources in the next century, especially, since China has such a huge population." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> A related plan can also accelerate some new industries and create employment opportunities. </seg>
<seg id=8> China has started to invest in the infrastructures, and work to overcome the impact caused by the Asian financial crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The Vice Secretary General of the meeting Zhongmo Zhuo said that: " The land is not only beneficial to the agricultural industry, but also provides for integrated  uses for many other industries, including forest industry, and tourist industry. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> China has been pushing the "one child" policy, however, China's population is expected to continue increasing, and will approach 1.6 billion by the middle of next century. </seg>
<seg id=11> Currently there are 1.2 billion people in China. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> More than 90% of the population lives on one third of the land in the country. </seg>
</p>
